About Us

Atlantic Investment Management is a fundamental, value-oriented equity investment firm founded by Alex Roepers in 1988. The firm’s investing methodology is differentiated by its: (1) well-defined universe of quality publicly-traded industrial / consumer companies; (2) concentration of capital and research on its highest conviction investments; (3) private equity-like due diligence; (4) constructive engagement with managements and boards to enhance and accelerate shareholder value; (5) strict adherence to its buy/sell cash flow focused valuation discipline; and (6) maintenance of liquidity to allow for opportunistic trading around core positions. Besides its flagship concentrated long-only U.S. and global best ideas funds, the firm manages long-biased hedge funds for each of the U.S., Europe, Japan and Asia ex-Japan markets. Atlantic has been a Registered Investment Adviser since 2006 and has 26 employees located in New York and Tokyo.
Learn More
Leadership

Alex Roepers, a 28-year hedge fund industry veteran, leads Atlantic Investment Management's 14-member investment team. The highly experienced analyst team has an average of 18 years of industry experience and an average firm tenure of 10 years, which has provided a strong foundation for investment process consistency and true collaboration across the team.
Learn More


News & Announcements


May 2, 2017Bloomberg TV
Bloomberg TV interviews Alex Roepers on Japan's economy, corporate reforms, and activism in Japan at the Milken Conference in Los Angeles on May 2, 2017.



September 8, 2016Institutional Investors Alpha: Unhedged Commentary: Finding Value in Value Stocks
Investment styles tend to move in multiyear cycles. We believe U.S. equity markets recently passed an important inflection point, heralding a rotation back to value investing. This rotation started as a result of stabilizing macro conditions and because many value stocks had become too cheap to ignore, in both absolute and relative terms.



April 23, 2016Barron's: Forgotten FMC's Attractions
Though its stock has risen some during the market’s recent rally, FMC, a midsize chemicals firm, remains a forgotten underperformer. Alexander Roepers, Atlantic Investment Management’s president believes “the company has self-help levers that should improve EPS significantly by 2018 or earlier” The agricultural cycle could roll over again, but given how low the shares remain, the downside seems limited compared to the upside.


View More






